message:
feat: refactor brain system, add history retention, and parallelize sensing

This commit modernizes the brain trait system with fixed-size array signatures,
implements in-memory history retention for tick summaries, parallelizes the
sensing stage using Rayon, and wires up full application-level integration with
DuckDB persistence. These enhancements complete the infrastructure needed for
production-ready simulation runs with analytics, improve type safety in the
brain API, and unlock multi-core performance for the sensing pipeline.

The brain refactoring eliminates heap allocations in the hot path by using
stack-allocated fixed-size arrays [f32; INPUT_SIZE] → [f32; OUTPUT_SIZE],
introduces BrainKind as a type-safe identifier replacing raw strings, and
provides an adapter pattern (BrainRunnerAdapter) that bridges trait
implementations to the simulation registry. History retention enables
real-time analytics by maintaining a bounded VecDeque of recent TickSummary
records, accessible via a public iterator. Sensing parallelization leverages
Rayon's parallel iterators to compute sensors concurrently across agents,
providing linear speedup on multi-core systems.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
BRAIN SYSTEM REFACTORING (crates/scriptbots-brain/src/lib.rs:1-118)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Architecture Overview:
The brain system has been refactored from a dynamic, allocation-heavy design
to a zero-allocation, type-safe system using fixed-size arrays. The Brain
trait now enforces compile-time array sizes, eliminating runtime bounds checks
and heap allocations in the simulation hot path. BrainKind provides a
lightweight newtype wrapper for brain family identification, replacing raw
string slices with a more idiomatic type. The adapter pattern enables clean
separation between the trait definition (brain behavior) and the simulation
runtime (BrainRunner registration).

BrainKind Newtype (lines 7-27):

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, Hash, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub struct BrainKind(&'static str);

impl BrainKind {
    #[must_use]
    pub const fn new(name: &'static str) -> Self {
        Self(name)
    }

    #[must_use]
    pub const fn as_str(self) -> &'static str {
        self.0
    }
}

impl From<&'static str> for BrainKind {
    fn from(value: &'static str) -> Self {
        Self::new(value)
    }
}
```

Design rationale:
• Newtype pattern: Strong typing prevents string confusion
• Copy: Zero-cost pass-by-value (single pointer)
• Eq + Hash: Enables use as HashMap key for brain registry
• Serialize + Deserialize: Supports genome persistence
• &'static str: Compile-time string literals (no runtime allocation)
• const fn: Compile-time construction (zero overhead)

Benefits over raw strings:
• Type safety: Compiler prevents using regular strings where BrainKind expected
• IDE support: Better autocomplete and refactoring
• Semantic clarity: Documents intent (this is a brain identifier)
• Future-proof: Can add validation, metadata, or registry lookup later

Brain Trait Modernization (lines 29-52):

Previous signature:
```rust
pub trait Brain {
    fn kind(&self) -> &'static str;
    fn tick(&mut self, inputs: &[f32]) -> Vec<f32>;
    fn mutate<R: Rng>(&mut self, rng: &mut R, rate: f32, scale: f32);
}
```

New signature:
```rust
pub trait Brain: Send + Sync {
    fn kind(&self) -> BrainKind;
    fn tick(&mut self, inputs: &[f32; INPUT_SIZE]) -> [f32; OUTPUT_SIZE];
    fn mutate(&mut self, rng: &mut dyn RngCore, rate: f32, scale: f32);
    fn crossover(&self, _other: &dyn Brain, _rng: &mut dyn RngCore)
        -> Option<Box<dyn Brain>> {
        None
    }
}
```

Key changes:

1. Send + Sync bounds:
   • Enables brain instances to move between threads
   • Required for parallel brain execution (future)
   • Safe: Brains own their state (no shared mutable references)

2. Fixed-size array inputs/outputs:
   • Before: &[f32] → Vec<f32> (heap allocation every tick)
   • After: &[f32; INPUT_SIZE] → [f32; OUTPUT_SIZE] (stack only)
   • Performance: Eliminates ~2 heap allocations per agent per tick
   • At 1000 agents, 60fps: 120,000 allocations/sec → 0 allocations/sec
   • Type safety: Compiler enforces correct sizes at compile time
   • Cache-friendly: Stack arrays have better locality

3. Dynamic trait objects for RNG:
   • Before: &mut impl Rng (generic, requires monomorphization)
   • After: &mut dyn RngCore (trait object, single implementation)
   • Rationale: Brains stored as trait objects (dyn Brain)
   • Cannot mix impl Trait with dyn Trait in same context
   • RngCore: Minimal interface (sufficient for mutation)
   • Tradeoff: Small virtual call overhead vs monomorphization bloat

4. Crossover hook:
   • Optional genetic algorithm operator
   • Default: None (not all brain types support crossover)
   • Return type: Option<Box<dyn Brain>> (heap allocation acceptable here)
   • Use case: MLP brains can crossover weights, others cannot
   • Pattern: Trait provides default, implementations override if supported

BrainRunnerAdapter Implementation (lines 87-114):

```rust
pub struct BrainRunnerAdapter<B: Brain> {
    brain: B,
}

impl<B: Brain> BrainRunnerAdapter<B> {
    #[must_use]
    pub fn new(brain: B) -> Self {
        Self { brain }
    }

    #[must_use]
    pub fn into_inner(self) -> B {
        self.brain
    }
}

impl<B: Brain> BrainRunner for BrainRunnerAdapter<B> {
    fn kind(&self) -> &'static str {
        self.brain.kind().as_str()
    }

    fn tick(&mut self, inputs: &[f32; INPUT_SIZE]) -> [f32; OUTPUT_SIZE] {
        self.brain.tick(inputs)
    }
}

#[must_use]
pub fn into_runner<B: Brain + 'static>(brain: B) -> Box<dyn BrainRunner> {
    Box::new(BrainRunnerAdapter::new(brain))
}
```

Adapter pattern purpose:
• Separates concerns: Brain (behavior) vs BrainRunner (registry interface)
• Enables trait object conversion: Brain → Box<dyn BrainRunner>
• Preserves concrete type: Can retrieve original brain via into_inner()
• Generic implementation: Works with any Brain implementation

BrainRunner trait (defined in scriptbots-core):
```rust
pub trait BrainRunner: Send {
    fn kind(&self) -> &'static str;
    fn tick(&mut self, inputs: &[f32; INPUT_SIZE]) -> [f32; OUTPUT_SIZE];
}
```

Why two traits?
• Brain: Rich interface for genetic operators (mutate, crossover)
• BrainRunner: Minimal interface for simulation runtime (tick only)
• Separation: Simulation doesn't need genetic operators during execution
• Flexibility: Can implement BrainRunner directly without Brain trait

Adapter workflow:
1. Implement Brain trait for custom brain type
2. Wrap in BrainRunnerAdapter::new(my_brain)
3. Box into trait object: Box::new(adapter)
4. Register in BrainRegistry
5. Simulation uses BrainRunner::tick() in hot path

into_runner() convenience:
• One-liner conversion: into_runner(my_brain)
• Returns Box<dyn BrainRunner> ready for registration
• Hides adapter boilerplate from users

Test Coverage (lines 54-86):

```rust
struct EchoBrain;

impl Brain for EchoBrain {
    fn kind(&self) -> BrainKind {
        BrainKind::new("echo")
    }

    fn tick(&mut self, inputs: &[f32; INPUT_SIZE]) -> [f32; OUTPUT_SIZE] {
        let mut outputs = [0.0; OUTPUT_SIZE];
        outputs[..OUTPUT_SIZE.min(INPUT_SIZE)]
            .copy_from_slice(&inputs[..OUTPUT_SIZE.min(INPUT_SIZE)]);
        outputs
    }

    fn mutate(&mut self, _rng: &mut dyn RngCore, _rate: f32, _scale: f32) {}
}

#[test]
fn adapter_forward_outputs() {
    let mut runner = BrainRunnerAdapter::new(EchoBrain);
    let mut inputs = [0.0; INPUT_SIZE];
    inputs[0] = 1.0;
    inputs[1] = 2.0;
    let outputs = runner.tick(&inputs);
    assert!((outputs[0] - 1.0).abs() < f32::EPSILON);
    assert!((outputs[1] - 2.0).abs() < f32::EPSILON);
}
```

Test validates:
• EchoBrain: Simple brain that copies inputs → outputs
• Adapter correctly forwards tick() calls
• Fixed-size arrays work end-to-end
• Output values match expected (epsilon comparison for floats)

