HISTORY RETENTION SYSTEM (crates/scriptbots-core/src/lib.rs)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Architecture Overview:
WorldState now maintains a bounded in-memory history of recent TickSummary
records via VecDeque. Each persistence flush appends the current summary to
the deque, evicting the oldest entry when capacity is reached. This enables
real-time analytics, debugging, and UI charting without re-querying the
database or maintaining external state.

Configuration (lines 1041-1042, 1076):

```rust
pub struct ScriptBotsConfig {
    // ... existing fields ...
    /// Maximum number of recent tick summaries retained in-memory.
    pub history_capacity: usize,
    /// Interval (ticks) between persistence flushes. 0 disables persistence.
    pub persistence_interval: u32,
}

impl Default for ScriptBotsConfig {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self {
            // ... other defaults ...
            history_capacity: 256,
            persistence_interval: 0,
        }
    }
}
```

Default rationale:
• history_capacity: 256 entries
  - At 60fps, persistence_interval=60 → 256 seconds (~4 minutes)
  - Reasonable memory usage: 256 × sizeof(TickSummary) ≈ 256 × 40 bytes = 10KB
  - Large enough for short-term trend analysis
  - Small enough to avoid memory bloat
• persistence_interval: 0 (disabled)
  - Explicit opt-in: Users enable persistence when needed
  - Zero overhead when unused

Validation (lines 1143-1148):

```rust
if self.reproduction_energy_threshold < 0.0
    || self.reproduction_energy_cost < 0.0
    || self.reproduction_child_energy < 0.0
    || self.reproduction_spawn_jitter < 0.0
    || self.reproduction_color_jitter < 0.0
    || self.reproduction_mutation_scale < 0.0
    || self.history_capacity == 0
{
    return Err(WorldStateError::InvalidConfig(
        "metabolism, reproduction, sharing, and history parameters must be non-negative, radius positive",
    ));
}
```

Constraint:
• history_capacity must be > 0
• Rationale: Zero capacity is nonsensical (cannot retain anything)
• Minimum: 1 (retains only most recent summary)
• Recommendation: ≥ 10 for meaningful trend analysis

WorldState Integration (lines 1266, 1299, 1316):

```rust
pub struct WorldState {
    // ... existing fields ...
    history: VecDeque<TickSummary>,
}

impl WorldState {
    pub fn with_persistence(
        config: ScriptBotsConfig,
        persistence: Box<dyn WorldPersistence>
    ) -> Result<Self, WorldStateError> {
        // ...
        let history_capacity = config.history_capacity;
        Ok(Self {
            // ... existing fields ...
            history: VecDeque::with_capacity(history_capacity),
        })
    }
}
```

VecDeque choice:
• Efficient FIFO: O(1) push_back, O(1) pop_front
• Bounded growth: Pre-allocated capacity prevents reallocation churn
• Cache-friendly: Contiguous memory (better than linked list)
• Standard library: No external dependencies

Alternative designs considered:
• Vec with circular buffer: More complex, VecDeque already optimized
• LinkedList: Poor cache locality, unnecessary pointer overhead
• Ringbuffer crate: External dependency, VecDeque sufficient
• Chosen: VecDeque (standard, efficient, simple)

Retention Logic (lines 1959-1963):

```rust
fn stage_persistence(&mut self, next_tick: Tick) {
    // ... compute summary ...
    self.persistence.on_tick(&summary);

    if self.history.len() >= self.config.history_capacity {
        self.history.pop_front();
    }
    self.history.push_back(summary);

    self.last_births = 0;
    self.last_deaths = 0;
}
```

Bounded queue behavior:
1. Append summary to back of deque
2. If length exceeds capacity, remove oldest (front)
3. Maintains exactly `capacity` entries (once filled)

Execution flow:
• Persistence sink receives summary first (on_tick)
• Then summary cloned into history deque
• Rationale: Persistence is primary, history is secondary cache
• Clone cost: TickSummary is small (7 fields, all Copy types)

Public API (lines 2038-2041):

```rust
/// Iterate over retained tick summaries.
#[must_use]
pub fn history(&self) -> impl Iterator<Item = &TickSummary> {
    self.history.iter()
}
```

Iterator design:
• Returns impl Iterator (opaque type, zero overhead)
• Items are &TickSummary (borrowed, no allocation)
• Consumer can collect, fold, or stream as needed
• #[must_use]: Warn if iterator ignored (common mistake)

Usage examples:

```rust
// Get most recent summary
if let Some(latest) = world.history().last() {
    println!("Tick {}: {} agents", latest.tick.0, latest.agent_count);
}

// Collect into Vec for analysis
let history: Vec<_> = world.history().cloned().collect();

// Compute average population over window
let avg_pop: f64 = world.history()
    .map(|s| s.agent_count as f64)
    .sum::<f64>() / world.history().count() as f64;

// Stream to UI chart
for summary in world.history() {
    chart.add_point(summary.tick.0, summary.average_energy);
}
```

