SENSING PARALLELIZATION (crates/scriptbots-core/src/lib.rs:1374-1425)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Architecture Overview:
The stage_sense() method has been parallelized using Rayon's parallel iterators,
distributing sensor computation across all available CPU cores. Each agent's
sensor array is computed independently in parallel, then copied back to the
runtime state in a second sequential pass. This provides near-linear speedup
on multi-core systems while maintaining deterministic results.

Previous Implementation:

```rust
fn stage_sense(&mut self) {
    // ... setup ...
    for (idx, agent_id) in handles.iter().enumerate() {
        let mut nearest_sq = f32::INFINITY;
        let mut neighbor_count = 0usize;
        // ... neighbor iteration ...

        if let Some(runtime) = self.runtime.get_mut(*agent_id) {
            runtime.sensors.fill(0.0);
            runtime.sensors[0] = (1.0 / (1.0 + nearest_dist)).clamp(0.0, 1.0);
            runtime.sensors[1] = (neighbor_count as f32 / neighbor_normalizer).clamp(0.0, 1.0);
            // ... fill remaining sensors ...
        }
    }
}
```

Characteristics:
• Sequential: Processes agents one-by-one
• Single-threaded: Uses only one CPU core
• Performance: O(n) time, but serial execution
• Bottleneck: Sensing dominates simulation time (index queries expensive)

New Parallel Implementation (lines 1374-1425):

```rust
fn stage_sense(&mut self) {
    use rayon::prelude::*;

    // ... setup ...
    let index = &self.index;

    let sensor_results: Vec<[f32; INPUT_SIZE]> = handles
        .par_iter()
        .enumerate()
        .map(|(idx, _agent_id)| {
            let mut sensors = [0.0f32; INPUT_SIZE];
            let mut nearest_sq = f32::INFINITY;
            let mut neighbor_count = 0usize;
            let mut neighbor_energy_sum = 0.0_f32;
            let mut neighbor_health_sum = 0.0_f32;

            index.neighbors_within(
                idx,
                radius_sq,
                &mut |other_idx, dist_sq: OrderedFloat<f32>| {
                    neighbor_count += 1;
                    let dist_sq_val = dist_sq.into_inner();
                    if dist_sq_val < nearest_sq {
                        nearest_sq = dist_sq_val;
                    }
                    neighbor_energy_sum += energies[other_idx];
                    neighbor_health_sum += health_slice[other_idx];
                },
            );

            // ... compute sensor values into local sensors array ...
            sensors
        })
        .collect();

    for (idx, agent_id) in handles.iter().enumerate() {
        if let Some(runtime) = self.runtime.get_mut(*agent_id) {
            runtime.sensors.copy_from_slice(&sensor_results[idx]);
        }
    }
}
```

Parallelization strategy:

1. Parallel computation phase:
   • handles.par_iter(): Rayon parallel iterator
   • enumerate(): Track agent index for result ordering
   • map(): Pure function (no shared mutable state)
   • Returns local sensors array (stack-allocated)
   • collect(): Gather results into Vec (heap allocation)

2. Sequential update phase:
   • Iterate handles again (same order)
   • Copy computed sensors into runtime.sensors
   • Mutates WorldState (cannot parallelize due to &mut self)

Why two phases?
• Phase 1 (parallel): Read-only access to index, energies, health
• Phase 2 (sequential): Mutable access to runtime
• Cannot hold &mut self while Rayon tasks run (borrow checker)
• Tradeoff: Vec allocation for parallelism (worth it for speedup)

Performance characteristics:

Theoretical speedup:
• Serial: T_total = n × T_query
• Parallel (p cores): T_total ≈ (n / p) × T_query + overhead
• Overhead: Vec allocation, thread synchronization
• Expected: ~0.8p speedup (80% parallel efficiency)

Benchmark expectations:
• 100 agents, 4 cores: ~3.2× speedup
• 1000 agents, 8 cores: ~6.4× speedup
• 10000 agents, 16 cores: ~12.8× speedup

When parallelism helps:
• Large agent counts (n > 100)
• Expensive queries (dense neighborhoods)
• Multi-core systems (p > 2)

When parallelism hurts:
• Small agent counts (n < 50): Overhead dominates
• Single-core systems: Thread overhead wasted
• Sparse worlds: Queries already fast

Memory overhead:
• Before: Zero extra allocation
• After: Vec<[f32; INPUT_SIZE]> = n × 7 × 4 bytes = 28n bytes
• Example: 1000 agents → 28KB (negligible)

Determinism preservation:
• enumerate() maintains index order
• collect() preserves ordering (guaranteed by Rayon)
• Sequential copy uses same index mapping
• Result: Identical output to serial version

Dependencies (Cargo.toml):

```toml
[workspace.dependencies]
rayon = "1.10.0"
```

```rust
use rayon::prelude::*;
```

Rayon benefits:
• Work-stealing: Automatic load balancing across threads
• Data parallelism: par_iter() drop-in replacement for iter()
• Zero-config: Uses all available cores by default
• Safety: Compiler prevents data races

Rayon overhead:
• Thread pool: One-time initialization cost
• Task scheduling: ~100ns per task
• Synchronization: Barrier at collect()
• Rule of thumb: Worthwhile if per-agent work > 1μs

Future optimizations:
• Parallel brain execution: Rayon over stage_brains()
• Parallel food queries: Par_iter over stage_food()
• Parallel reproduction: Par_iter over stage_reproduction()
• Bottleneck: SlotMap mutations (sequential)

